\par First Press the group key you want to send the order to. The screen will show a prompt of supported commands just under the target reticule. Then press the command you would like to give. Most commands complete at this point, and your wingmen will take ac
tion.
\par 
\par Some commands need further menu input (such as cargo and group commands). You will be prompted for more input.
\par 
\par You can cancel a command sequence by }{\insrsid2165678 pressing the back quote (left of}{\insrsid3810134  the 1 key). 
\par }\pard\plain \s3\ql \li0\ri0\sb240\sa60\keepn\widctlpar\aspalpha\aspnum\faauto\outlinelevel2\adjustright\rin0\lin0\itap0 \b\f1\fs26\lang1033\langfe1033\cgrid\langnp1033\langfenp1033 {\insrsid2165678 Group Submenu}{\insrsid3810134 
\par }\pard\plain \ql \li0\ri0\widctlpar\aspalpha\aspnum\faauto\adjustright\rin0\lin0\itap0 \fs24\lang1033\langfe1033\cgrid\langnp1033\langfenp1033 {\insrsid3810134 Group commands are a little bit special. 
They are used to add and remove ships from a group. With group commands, the first key press selects the group you want to operate on (instead of the group you will give an order to). 
\par 
\par For example, to add a wingman to group one, you would press 1 (select group one) \endash  0 (group commands) \endash  0 (add ship to group).
\par 
\par Removing a ship from a group will automatically add the ship to group zero. This is because all player wingmen must belong to a group.
\par }\pard\plain \s3\ql \li0\ri0\sb240\sa60\keepn\widctlpar\aspalpha\aspnum\faauto\outlinelevel2\adjustright\rin0\lin0\itap0 \b\f1\fs26\lang1033\langfe1033\cgrid\langnp1033\langfenp1033 {\insrsid2165678 Cargo Submenu}{\insrsid3810134 
